  "What is a 'quantum state' in the language of linear algebra?": "",
  "Any vector in R^3, particularly regarding provides when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "An eigenvalue of the Hamiltonian according to conventional analysis": "",
  "A real-valued function of position in the context of this analysis": "",
  "A unit vector in a complex Hilbert space, representing the complete description of a quantum system": "",
  "A pure quantum state is a unit vector |psi> in a complex Hilbert space H with ||psi|| = 1. The Hilbert space structure (inner product, completeness) provides the mathematical framework for quantum probability.": "",
  "What is the 'Hamiltonian' in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "A Hermitian operator representing the total energy of the system, whose eigenvalues are the allowed energy levels": "",
  "A vector representing the system's momentum": "",
  "A unitary operator representing time evolution": "",
  "A scalar representing the system's temperature": "",
  "The Hamiltonian H is a Hermitian matrix (or operator) whose eigenvalues are the system's energy levels and whose eigenvectors are the energy eigenstates. It drives time evolution via U(t) = e^{-iHt/hbar}.": "",
  "What does 'measurement' mean in the quantum linear algebra framework?": "",
  "Computing the trace of the state vector when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "Finding the determinant of the observable under normal circumstances": "",
  "Projecting the state vector onto an eigenspace of the observable, with probability given by the squared projection magnitude": "",
  "Multiplying the state by a unitary matrix in most standard conditions": "",
  "Quantum measurement of observable A on state |psi> projects |psi> onto one of A's eigenspaces. The outcome is eigenvalue lambda_i with probability |P_i|psi>|^2, and the post-measurement state is P_i|psi>/||P_i|psi>||.": "",
  "What is a 'tensor product' in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "The dot product of two quantum states, particularly regarding mechanics when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "The sum of two Hilbert spaces, particularly regarding joint as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "The matrix product of two operators, particularly regarding creates when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "The mathematical operation that combines two quantum systems into a composite system, with the combined Hilbert space being the tensor product of the individual spaces": "",
  "The tensor product H_A (x) H_B creates the composite Hilbert space for two quantum systems. If system A is in C^m and B is in C^n, the joint system lives in C^{mn}. This exponential growth enables quantum computational advantage.": "",
  "What is 'quantum entanglement' mathematically?": "",
  "A state in the tensor product space that cannot be written as a single tensor product of states from each subsystem": "",
  "A state that is an eigenvector of the total Hamiltonian": "",
  "A superposition of exactly two basis states": "",
  "Two particles that are close together in space": "",
  "An entangled state |psi> in H_A (x) H_B cannot be factored as |a> (x) |b>. Entanglement is detected by the Schmidt rank: if the state has more than one term in its Schmidt decomposition, it is entangled.": "",
  "What is the 'Schmidt decomposition'?": "",
  "A bipartite state can be written as sum of lambda_i |a_i> (x) |b_i> with orthonormal {|a_i>} and {|b_i>}": "",
  "Any quantum state can be decomposed into real and imaginary parts": "",
  "A decomposition of unitary gates into single-qubit and CNOT gates": "",
  "The eigendecomposition of the Hamiltonian": "",
  "The Schmidt decomposition is the SVD applied to the coefficient matrix of a bipartite quantum state. The Schmidt coefficients lambda_i quantify entanglement: a state is entangled iff it has more than one nonzero Schmidt coefficient.": "",
  "What is 'quantum decoherence' in terms of density matrices?": "",
  "The increase of the trace of the density matrix": "",
  "The loss of energy from a quantum system": "",
  "The process where off-diagonal entries of the density matrix decay toward zero, turning a pure state into a mixed state": "",
  "The collapse of a superposition to a single eigenstate": "",
  "Decoherence causes the off-diagonal elements (coherences) of the density matrix to decay, transforming a pure state rho = |psi><psi| (with coherences) into an approximately diagonal mixed state. This explains the transition from quantum to classical behavior.": "",
  "What is the 'trace distance' between two quantum states?": "",
  "D(rho, sigma) = (1/2) trace(|rho - sigma|) where |A| = sqrt(A*A)": "",
  "The Euclidean distance between their eigenvalue vectors": "",
  "The sum of their traces": "",
  "The absolute difference of their traces": "",
  "The trace distance D = (1/2)||rho - sigma||_1 measures the maximum probability of distinguishing two quantum states. It uses the trace norm (sum of singular values) and ranges from 0 (identical) to 1 (orthogonal).": "",
  "What is a 'quantum channel' mathematically?": "",
  "A Hermitian matrix representing an observable": "",
  "A projection operator": "",
  "A completely positive, trace-preserving linear map on density matrices": "",
  "A unitary transformation only": "",
  "A quantum channel E is a linear map on density matrices that is completely positive (preserves positivity even on extended systems) and trace-preserving (trace(E(rho)) = 1). It describes the most general physical evolution of a quantum state.": "",
  "What is the 'fidelity' between two quantum states?": "",
  "F(rho, sigma) = (trace(sqrt(sqrt(rho) sigma sqrt(rho))))^2, measuring their overlap": "",
  "The trace of rho + sigma": "",
  "The largest eigenvalue of rho - sigma": "",
  "The determinant of rho * sigma": "",
  "Fidelity measures how close two quantum states are. For pure states, F = |<psi|phi>|^2. For mixed states, the general formula involves matrix square roots. F ranges from 0 (orthogonal) to 1 (identical).": "",
  "A quantum computing researcher prepares a 2-qubit state |psi> = (1/sqrt(3))|00> + (1/sqrt(3))|01> + (1/sqrt(3))|10>. What is the reduced density matrix of the first qubit obtained by tracing out the second qubit?": "",
  "[[2/3, 1/3], [1/3, 1/3]]": "",
  "[[1/3, 0], [0, 2/3]]": "",
  "[[1/2, 0], [0, 1/2]]": "",
  "[[1, 0], [0, 0]]": "",
  "rho_1 = trace_2(|psi><psi|). Writing |psi> = |0>(1/sqrt(3)|0>+1/sqrt(3)|1>) + |1>(1/sqrt(3)|0>): rho_1,00 = 1/3+1/3=2/3, rho_1,11 = 1/3, rho_1,01 = 1/3*1 = 1/3, rho_1,10 = 1/3. So rho_1 = [[2/3, 1/3],[1/3, 1/3]].": "",
  "A physicist models a two-level atom interacting with a laser. The Hamiltonian is H = [[E_0, Omega], [Omega, E_1]] where Omega is the coupling strength. If E_0 = 0, E_1 = 8, and Omega = 3, what are the eigenvalues (dressed state energies)?": "",
  "0 and 8": "",
  "-1 and 9": "",
  "1 and 7": "",
  "-3 and 11": "",
  "H = [[0,3],[3,8]]. Eigenvalues: lambda = (0+8)/2 +/- sqrt((8-0)^2/4 + 9) = 4 +/- sqrt(16+9) = 4 +/- 5, giving lambda = 9 and lambda = -1. The coupling shifts the bare energies (0 and 8) to the dressed energies (-1 and 9).": "",
  "A quantum error correction researcher uses the 3-qubit bit-flip code. The logical |0_L> = |000> and |1_L> = |111>. The syndrome measurement operators are Z_1Z_2 and Z_2Z_3. If a bit-flip error occurs on qubit 2, what syndrome does Z_1Z_2 give?": "",
  "-1": "",
  "+1": "",
  "i": "",
  "If |000> becomes |010> after a bit-flip on qubit 2, Z_1Z_2|010> = (+1)(-1)|010> = -|010>. The eigenvalue -1 indicates qubits 1 and 2 disagree, helping locate the error.": "",
  "A quantum algorithm designer implements Grover's search on 3 qubits (N=8 items). The key operation is the Grover iterate G = (2|psi><psi| - I) * O_f, where O_f marks the target. How many iterations are needed to find the target with high probability?": "",
